  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation to combat money laundering has evolved significantly over the past few decades:\n\n1. Early Developments\n- 1970 Bank Secrecy Act (US) first introduced reporting requirements\n- 1989 Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established\n- Criminalized money laundering in many jurisdictions\n\n2. Key Milestones\n- 1990s: Enhanced international cooperation\n- Increased reporting requirements for financial institutions\n- Expanded scope of predicate offenses\n- Stricter customer due diligence regulations\n\n3. Post-9/11 Changes\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001) expanded anti-money laundering (AML) provisions\n- Greater focus on terrorism financing\n- Enhanced information sharing between agencies\n\n4. Recent Trends\n- Cryptocurrency regulation\n- Beneficial ownership transparency requirements\n- Enhanced digital transaction monitoring\n- Risk-based approach to compliance\n- Increased digital forensic capabilities\n\n5. Global Standards\n- FATF recommendations becoming more comprehensive\n- Coordinated international enforcement\n- Stricter penalties for non-compliance\n- Technology-driven compliance mechanisms\n\n6. Emerging Challenges\n- Complex financial technologies\n- Cross-border transaction complexities\n- Increasing sophistication of money laundering techniques\n\nLegislation continues to adapt to technological and financial innovations.",
